from pymongo import MongoClient
import pandas as pd
import json

def load_data_to_mongo(mongo_uri, database_name, collection_name, csv_file_path):
    """
    Load data from a CSV file into a MongoDB collection.

    Args:
        mongo_uri (str): "mongodb+srv://vhe9uc:uva2025@cluster0.qo2st.mongodb.net/test?retryWrites=true&w=majority".
        database_name (str): "DS2002FinalProject".
        collection_name (str): "Cost_of_living".
        csv_file_path (str): "merged_dataset.csv".
    """
    try:
        # Connect to MongoDB
        client = MongoClient(mongo_uri)
        db = client[database_name]
        collection = db[collection_name]

        # Load data from CSV into a pandas DataFrame
        data = pd.read_csv(csv_file_path)

        # Convert DataFrame to JSON
        data_json = json.loads(data.to_json(orient="records"))

        # Insert data into the MongoDB collection
        collection.insert_many(data_json)

        print(f"Data successfully loaded into MongoDB collection '{collection_name}'.")

    except Exception as e:
        print(f"An error occurred: {e}")

    finally:
        # Close the MongoDB connection
        client.close()

if __name__ == "__main__":
    mongo_uri = "mongodb+srv://vhe9uc:uva2025@cluster0.qo2st.mongodb.net/test?retryWrites=true&w=majority"
    database_name = "DS2002FinalProject"
    collection_name = "Cost_of_living"
    csv_file_path = "merged_dataset.csv"

    load_data_to_mongo(mongo_uri, database_name, collection_name, csv_file_path)

data = pd.read_csv('DATA/merged_dataset.csv')

# Setup
print("Dataset Overview:")
display(data.head())

print("\nSummary Statistics:")
display(data.describe())

print("\nMissing Values:")
missing_values = data.isnull().sum()
display(missing_values[missing_values > 0])

data.fillna(data.mean(numeric_only=True), inplace=True)
print("\nMissing values handled. Re-checking:")
display(data.isnull().sum())

print("\nData Types:")
display(data.dtypes)

# Distribution of a categorical column
if 'Urban_population' in data.columns:
    print("\nDistribution of Urban Population:")
    display(data['Urban_population'].value_counts())

# Feature distribution comparison
columns_to_compare = ['Cost of Living Index', 'Rent Index', 'Groceries Index', 'Restaurant Price Index']
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
data[columns_to_compare].boxplot()
plt.title("Boxplot of Indices")
plt.ylabel("Index Value")
plt.show()

# Correlation heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.heatmap(data.corr(numeric_only=True), annot=True, cmap='coolwarm')
plt.title("Correlation Heatmap")
plt.show()

# Pairplot for a subset of columns
subset_data = data[['Cost of Living Index', 'Rent Index', 'Groceries Index', 'Local Purchasing Power Index']]
sns.pairplot(data=subset_data)
plt.suptitle("Pairplot of Key Indices", y=1.02)
plt.show()

# Top 10 countries by Local Purchasing Power Index
top_local_power = data.nlargest(10, 'Local Purchasing Power Index')
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.barplot(data=top_local_power, x='Local Purchasing Power Index', y='Country', palette='coolwarm')
plt.title("Top 10 Countries by Local Purchasing Power Index")
plt.xlabel("Local Purchasing Power Index")
plt.ylabel("Country")
plt.show()

# Geographical Visualization: Scatterplot with Latitude and Longitude
if 'Latitude' in data.columns and 'Longitude' in data.columns:
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.scatterplot(data=data, x='Longitude', y='Latitude', hue='Cost of Living Index', palette='coolwarm', size='Population', sizes=(20, 200))
    plt.title("Geographical Scatterplot: Cost of Living Index")
    plt.xlabel("Longitude")
    plt.ylabel("Latitude")
    plt.legend(title="Cost of Living Index", bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
    plt.show()

# Trend Analysis: Relationship between Cost of Living Index and another metric 
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
sns.regplot(data=data, x='Cost of Living Index', y='Birth Rate', scatter_kws={"color": "blue"}, line_kws={"color": "red"})
plt.title("Regression Analysis: Cost of Living Index vs Birt Rate")
plt.xlabel("Cost of Living Index")
plt.ylabel("Birth Rate")
plt.show()

key_columns = ['Cost of Living Index', 'Rent Index', 'Groceries Index', 'Restaurant Price Index']
# Median and Quartile Range
print("\nStatistical Analysis - Median and IQR:")
for col in key_columns:
    q1 = data[col].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = data[col].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3 - q1
    print(f"{col}: Median = {data[col].median():.2f}, IQR = {iqr:.2f}")

Analysis¶

1. Boxplot Analysis¶

  • Indices Distribution: From the boxplot of Cost of Living Index, Rent Index, Groceries Index, and Restaurant Price Index, the following patterns were observed:
    • Cost of Living Index has the largest range, with outliers indicating countries with extremely high costs.
    • Rent Index has the most compact distribution, but outliers suggest a few countries have significantly higher rents.
    • Groceries Index and Restaurant Price Index also exhibit outliers, showing variability among countries.

2. Correlation Heatmap¶

  • High Correlations:
    • Cost of Living Index and Rent Index have a strong positive correlation (0.83), suggesting rent significantly influences living costs.
    • Cost of Living Plus Rent Index correlates highly with both its components (Cost of Living Index and Rent Index).
  • Low/Negative Correlations:
    • Local Purchasing Power Index shows a weak negative correlation with Cost of Living Index, implying that high costs do not always align with strong purchasing power.
    • Fertility Rate and Life Expectancy negatively correlate, showing potential socioeconomic trends.

3. Pairplot¶

  • The pairplot reveals linear relationships between indices:
    • Cost of Living Index vs. Rent Index: A clear upward trend indicates that higher rent is associated with higher living costs.
    • Groceries Index aligns closely with the Cost of Living Index, indicating food prices heavily influence living costs.

4. Top Countries by Local Purchasing Power Index¶

  • Top Countries:
    • Luxembourg, Kuwait, and Qatar lead with the highest purchasing power, suggesting robust economic conditions and affordability relative to income levels.
  • Insights:
    • These countries tend to have higher incomes relative to living costs, which benefits residents' financial capacity.

5. Geographical Analysis¶

  • Cost of Living by Location:
    • Europe and parts of Asia show clusters of high living costs (e.g., Switzerland, Singapore).
    • Larger bubbles indicate higher population densities, with notable countries including the United States and Singapore.
  • Observation:
    • Some high-cost countries (e.g., Switzerland) have low population density, whereas others (e.g., Singapore) have high densities.

6. Regression Analysis¶

  • Cost of Living Index vs. Rent Index:
    • A regression plot reveals a significant linear relationship, indicating that rent contributes substantially to overall living costs.

7. Statistical Analysis¶

  • Central Tendencies:
    • The median values for indices (e.g., Cost of Living Index, Rent Index) are lower than the mean, indicating positive skewness with a few countries having exceptionally high values.
  • Interquartile Range (IQR):
    • High IQRs for indices like Cost of Living Index suggest substantial variability across countries.

Key Takeaways¶

  1. Cost of Living and Rent:

    • Rent is a key driver of the cost of living, especially in developed nations.
    • Policymakers should consider housing affordability as a critical factor in overall economic planning.

  2. Regional Insights:

    • Europe dominates the high-cost category, with countries like Switzerland consistently ranking highest.
    • However, regions with high purchasing power (e.g., Luxembourg, Qatar) balance living costs effectively through higher incomes.

  3. Economic Patterns:

    • Socioeconomic indicators like Fertility Rate and Life Expectancy highlight global disparities, with higher living standards associated with lower fertility rates.

  4. Geographical Influence:

    • Geographic location impacts living costs, with high-density cities (e.g., Singapore) exhibiting unique challenges despite smaller geographic areas.
